In regard to religion, Socrates, while often employing language

suited to the popular polytheism, held that there was one supreme God who was to the universe what the soul of man was to his body, that all things were arranged and ordered by Him for good, and that man was the objectos His special providence and might look for guidanee from Him in eracles and otherwise. The soul was immortal, and had in it a divine element Socrates believed that he was himself favoured beyond others in the warning sign (τὸ δαιμόνιον) which checked him whenever he was about to take an ill-judged step.

The personal enmity provoked by the use of the Socratis aleretur, and themora general dislike to the Socratis method as unsettling the grounds of belief and undermining authority, adislilre which showed itself in the Olouds of Aristophanes as early as 423 aa, combined with the democratia reaction, after the overthrow of the Thirty, to bring about the execution of Socrates in the year 399 ac. The charges on which he was condemned were that he did not believe in the Gods of the established religion, that he introduced new Gods, and that he corrupted the young: the last charge probably referring to the fact that Socrates freely pointed out the faults of the Athenian constitution, and that many of his disciples took the anti-popular side (N. D. 11 18, 167).

Our authorities for the life of Socrates are the writings of his two disciples, Xenophon and Plato. The former (440-355 sc.) was a soldier and country gentlemau with a taste for literature, who endeavoured to clear his master’s memory from the imputationes impiety and immorality hy publishing the Memorabilia, a collection of bis noteworthy sayings and discourses. Xenophon was banished from Athens for fighting in the Spartan ranke at Coronea. Plato is distinguished from the other disciples of Socrates as the one who represents most truly the many-sidedness of his master, completing indeed and developing what was defective in him and incorporating all that was valuable in the earlier philosophare Before treating of him it will be convenient to speak shortly of the ‘imperfect' or one-sided Socraticists.
